[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] For the basic usage introduction we will be installing `pendulum`, a datetime library.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If you have not yet installed Poetry, refer to the Introduction chapter.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] The `pyproject.toml` file is what is the most important here.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] This will orchestrate your project and its dependencies.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Poetry assumes your package contains a package with the same name as `project.name` located in the root of your project.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If this is not the case, populate `tool.poetry.packages` to specify your packages and their locations.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Similarly, the traditional `MANIFEST.in` file is replaced by the `project.readme`, `tool.poetry.include`, and `tool.poetry.exclude` sections.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] `tool.poetry.exclude` is additionally implicitly populated by your `.gitignore`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] For full documentation on the project format, see the pyproject section of the documentation.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Unlike with other packages, Poetry will not automatically install a python interpreter for you.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Poetry will require you to explicitly specify what versions of Python you intend to support, and its universal locking will guarantee that your project is installable (and all dependencies claim support for) all supported Python versions.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Again, it’s important to remember that – unlike other dependencies – setting a Python version is merely specifying which versions of Python you intend to support.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] we are allowing any version of Python 3 that is greater or equal than `3.9.0`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] When you run `poetry install`, you must have access to some version of a Python interpreter that satisfies this constraint available on your system.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Poetry will not install a Python interpreter for you.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Instead of creating a new project, Poetry can be used to ‘initialize’ a pre-populated directory.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Poetry can be operated in two different modes.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] The default mode is the **package mode**, which is the right mode if you want to package your project into an sdist or a wheel and perhaps publish it to a package index.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] In this mode, some metadata such as `name` and `version`, which are required for packaging, are mandatory.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Further, the project itself will be installed in editable mode when running `poetry install`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] In this mode, metadata such as `name` and `version` are optional.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Therefore, it is not possible to build a distribution or publish the project to a package index.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Further, when running `poetry install`, Poetry does not try to install the project itself, but only its dependencies (same as `poetry install --no-root`).
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] you can see which fields are required in package mode.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If you want to add dependencies to your project, you can specify them in the `project` section.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] As you can see, it takes a mapping of **package names** and **version constraints**.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Poetry uses this information to search for the right set of files in package “repositories” that you register in the `tool.poetry.source` section, or on PyPI by default.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Also, instead of modifying the `pyproject.toml` file by hand, you can use the `add` command.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] It will automatically find a suitable version constraint **and install** the package and sub-dependencies.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Poetry supports a rich dependency specification syntax, including caret, tilde, wildcard, inequality and multiple constraints requirements.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] By default, Poetry creates a virtual environment in `{cache-dir}/virtualenvs`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] You can change the `cache-dir` value by editing the Poetry configuration.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Additionally, you can use the `virtualenvs.in-project` configuration variable to create virtual environments within your project directory.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] There are several ways to run commands within this virtual environment.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Poetry will detect and respect an existing virtual environment that has been externally activated.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] This is a powerful mechanism that is intended to be an alternative to Poetry’s built-in, simplified environment management.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] To take advantage of this, simply activate a virtual environment using your preferred method or tooling, before running any Poetry commands that expect to manipulate an environment.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] To run your script simply use `poetry run python your_script.py`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Likewise if you have command line tools such as `pytest` or `black` you can run them using `poetry run pytest`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If managing your own virtual environment externally, you do not need to use `poetry run` since you will, presumably, already have activated that virtual environment and made available the correct python instance.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] In our example, we are requesting the `pendulum` package with the version constraint `>=2.1.0 <3.0.0`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] This means any version greater or equal to 2.1.0 and less than 3.0.0.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Please read Dependency specification for more in-depth information on versions, how versions relate to each other, and on the different ways you can specify dependencies.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] When you specify a dependency in `pyproject.toml`, Poetry first takes the name of the package that you have requested and searches for it in any repository you have registered using the `repositories` key.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If you have not registered any extra repositories, or it does not find a package with that name in the repositories you have specified, it falls back to PyPI.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] When Poetry finds the right package, it then attempts to find the best match for the version constraint you have specified.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] To install the defined dependencies for your project, just run the `install` command.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If you have never run the command before and there is also no `poetry.lock` file present, Poetry simply resolves all dependencies listed in your `pyproject.toml` file and downloads the latest version of their files.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] When Poetry has finished installing, it writes all the packages and their exact versions that it downloaded to the `poetry.lock` file, locking the project to those specific versions.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] You should commit the `poetry.lock` file to your project repo so that all people working on the project are locked to the same versions of dependencies (more below).
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If there is already a `poetry.lock` file as well as a `pyproject.toml` file when you run `poetry install`, it means either you ran the `install` command before, or someone else on the project ran the `install` command and committed the `poetry.lock` file to the project (which is good).
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Either way, running `install` when a `poetry.lock` file is present resolves and installs all dependencies that you listed in `pyproject.toml`, but Poetry uses the exact versions listed in `poetry.lock` to ensure that the package versions are consistent for everyone working on your project.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] As a result you will have all dependencies requested by your `pyproject.toml` file, but they may not all be at the very latest available versions (some dependencies listed in the `poetry.lock` file may have released newer versions since the file was created).
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] This is by design, it ensures that your project does not break because of unexpected changes in dependencies.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Application developers commit `poetry.lock` to get more reproducible builds.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Committing this file to VC is important because it will cause anyone who sets up the project to use the exact same versions of the dependencies that you are using.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Your CI server, production machines, other developers in your team, everything and everyone runs on the same dependencies, which mitigates the potential for bugs affecting only some parts of the deployments.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Even if you develop alone, in six months when reinstalling the project you can feel confident the dependencies installed are still working even if your dependencies released many new versions since then.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] However, pip will not use the lock file to determine dependency versions as the poetry-core build system is intended for library developers (see next section).
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Library developers have more to consider.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Your users are application developers, and your library will run in a Python environment you don’t control.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] The application ignores your library’s lock file.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] It can use whatever dependency version meets the constraints in your `pyproject.toml`.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] The application will probably use the latest compatible dependency version.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If your library’s `poetry.lock` falls behind some new dependency version that breaks things for your users, you’re likely to be the last to find out about it.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] A simple way to avoid such a scenario is to omit the `poetry.lock` file.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] However, by doing so, you sacrifice reproducibility and performance to a certain extent.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Without a lockfile, it can be difficult to find the reason for failing tests, because in addition to obvious code changes an unnoticed library update might be the culprit.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Further, Poetry will have to lock before installing a dependency if `poetry.lock` has been omitted.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] Depending on the number of dependencies, locking may take a significant amount of time.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] If you do not want to give up the reproducibility and performance benefits, consider a regular refresh of `poetry.lock` to stay up-to-date and reduce the risk of sudden breakage for users.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] The current project is installed in editable mode by default.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] As mentioned above, the `poetry.lock` file prevents you from automatically getting the latest versions of your dependencies.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] To update to the latest versions, use the `update` command.
[src:poetry-python/basic-usage] This will fetch the latest matching versions (according to your `pyproject.toml` file) and update the lock file with the new versions.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Dependencies for a project can be specified in various forms, which depend on the type of the dependency and on the optional constraints that might be needed for it to be installed.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Prior Poetry 2.0, dependencies had to be declared in the `tool.poetry.dependencies` section of the `pyproject.toml` file.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] With Poetry 2.0, you should consider using the `project.dependencies` section instead.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] While dependencies in `tool.poetry.dependencies` are specified using toml tables, dependencies in `project.dependencies` are specified as strings according to PEP 508.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] In many cases, `tool.poetry.dependencies` can be replaced with `project.dependencies`.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] However, there are some cases where you might still need to use `tool.poetry.dependencies`.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] For example, if you want to define additional information that is not required for building but only for locking (for example, an explicit source), you can enrich dependency information in the `tool.poetry` section.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] When both are specified, `project.dependencies` are used for metadata when building the project, `tool.poetry.dependencies` is only used to enrich `project.dependencies` for locking.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Alternatively, you can add `dependencies` to `dynamic` and define your dependencies completely in the `tool.poetry` section.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Using only the `tool.poetry` section might make sense in non-package mode when you will not build an sdist or a wheel.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] `~=1.2.3` is an example of a compatible release requirement.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] `*`, `1.*` and `1.2.*` are examples of wildcard requirements.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Multiple version requirements can also be separated with a comma, e.g.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] You can specify the exact version of a package.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] `1.2.3` is an example of an exact version specification.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] This will tell Poetry to install this version and this version only.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] If other dependencies require a different version, the solver will ultimately fail and abort any installation or update procedures.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Exact versions can also be specified with `==` according to PEP 440.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Not supported in `project.dependencies`.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] When using `poetry add` such constraints are automatically converted into an equivalent constraint.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] `~1.2.3` is an example of a tilde requirement.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] When adding dependencies via `poetry add`, you can use the `@` operator.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] This is understood similarly to the `==` syntax, but also allows prefixing any specifiers that are valid in `pyproject.toml`.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Since we haven’t specified any other information, Poetry assumes that we intend to use the latest commit on the `main` branch to build our project.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Combine the `git` key with the `branch`, `rev` or `tag` key respectively.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] It’s possible to add a package that is located in a subdirectory of the VCS repository.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Provide the subdirectory as a URL fragment similarly to what pip provides.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] To use HTTP basic authentication with your git repositories, you can configure credentials similar to how repository credentials are configured.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] We fall back to legacy system git client implementation in cases where gitcredentials is used.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] This fallback will be removed in a future release where `gitcredentials` helpers can be better supported natively.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] In cases where you encounter issues with the default implementation, you may wish to explicitly configure the use of the system git client via a shell subprocess call.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] To install directory path dependencies in editable mode, use the `develop` keyword and set it to `true`.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] `url` dependencies are libraries located on a remote archive.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] You can specify PEP-508 Extras for a dependency as shown here.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Poetry populates the `extra` marker with each of the selected extras of the root package.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] `pathlib2` will be installed when you install your package with `--extras paths` on a `win32` machine.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] This was a new feature of Poetry 2.0 and became the default behavior in Poetry 2.3.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Keep in mind that all combinations of possible extras available in your project need to be compatible with each other.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] This means that in order to use differing or incompatible versions across different combinations, you need to make your extra markers *exclusive*.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] For the CPU case, we have to specify `"extra != 'cuda'"` because the version specified is not compatible with the GPU (`cuda`) version.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Sometimes, one of your dependencies may have different version ranges depending on the target Python versions.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] ) otherwise it will cause an error when resolving dependencies.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Direct origin (`git`/ `url`/ `path`) dependencies can satisfy the requirement of a dependency that doesn’t explicitly specify a source, even when mutually exclusive markers are used.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] Sometimes you may instead want to use a direct origin dependency for specific conditions (i.e., a compiled package that is not available on PyPI for a certain platform/architecture) while falling back on source repositories in other cases.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] In this case you should explicitly ask for your dependency to be satisfied by another `source`.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] In the case of more complex dependency specifications, you may find that you end up with lines which are very long and difficult to read.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] In these cases, you can shift from using “inline table” syntax to the “standard table” syntax.
[src:poetry-python/dependency-specification] As a single line, this is a lot to digest.
